# Metadata at Scale
# Shows how AI-extracted metadata enables business intelligence queries
# across a large contracts library — filtering, aggregating, and cross-referencing
# at a scale that document search alone cannot support.

[var: SITE = https://microsoft.sharepoint-df.com/teams/ZachDemos/]
[category: Lists & Data]

[section: setup]

Verify the contracts document library is loaded and that the metadata columns are
populated — Risk Level, Document Type, Contract Quarter, Has Termination Clause,
Has Indemnification Clause, Energy Category, Continent, and Complexity.

[navigate: ${SITE}]

[open-chat]

[new-chat]

[section: demo]

[navigate: ${SITE}Contracts/]

AI can summarize a contract in seconds. But ask it to find every contract in your
library that's missing a termination clause — and most tools fall apart. Not
because AI isn't capable. Because they're missing one thing. Let me show you what
that is.

[pause]

So here's a SharePoint document library — this is a contracts repository. Hundreds
of contracts. And at first glance this looks like any other document library.

Look at these columns. Risk Level. Document Type. Contract Quarter. Energy Category.
Continent. Complexity.

This metadata was extracted automatically by AI at upload time — pulled right out of
the contract text and stamped onto each document as structured fields.

[pause]

You might ask: if AI is doing the extracting anyway, why bother storing it? Why not
just let AI read the document every time?

Three reasons. Scale — you don't have one contract, you have hundreds. Reading every
document fresh for every question isn't a chat experience, it's a bill. Consistency
— if you classify risk by reading a contract fresh each time you might get a slightly
different answer each day. Extract it once and that answer is locked, stable,
something your legal team can actually trust. And the big one: there are entire
categories of questions that search simply cannot answer without metadata.

[pause]

[open-chat]

Watch this.

[prompt: Find all contracts classified as High Risk.]

[wait]

Instead of searching document text — which would miss contracts where the words
"high risk" never appear verbatim — the AI filters the Risk column directly. Like a
database query. Every single one. Not a best guess. All of them. Complete and
auditable.

[pause]

Now here's where it gets interesting.

[prompt: Among all High Risk contracts, what percentage include indemnification clauses?]

[wait]

This is the question that breaks every standard AI tool. It's actually two problems
in sequence — first define the universe, then analyze across it. Without metadata
you don't have a reliable universe. You have a guess. With metadata, AI locks onto
every High Risk contract — it knows exactly what's in scope — and then reads those
specific documents for indemnification language and calculates the percentage.

That's not a chat experience anymore. That's a business intelligence query. On your
document library.

[pause]

One more.

[prompt: Retrieve all Joint Venture Agreements signed in Q4 2019.]

[wait]

Type filter. Date filter. Two columns. Instant. In a standard system, dates are
buried in document text in a dozen different formats, and document types get
described differently across hundreds of files. This query would be unreliable at
best. Here it's deterministic — the metadata was standardized at ingestion.

[screenshot: tools/screenshots/metadata-at-scale.png]

The difference is this. Regular AI reads documents and hopes it found the right
ones. Metadata-augmented AI knows the shape of your entire library before it reads
a single word — how many documents exist, how they're classified, what risk they
carry. You do the extraction work once. And then every question, every filter, every
analysis runs on that foundation forever.

[pause]

